  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are numerous legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. BCCI (Bank of Credit and Commerce International)\n- Landmark case involving international banking fraud\n- Significant penalties and widespread regulatory reforms\n\n2. United States v. Levesque\n- Established guidelines for proving intent in money laundering\n- Defined specific elements of financial transaction criminality\n\n3. United States v. Santos\n- Supreme Court case clarifying definition of \"proceeds\" in money laundering statutes\n- Established important interpretive principles\n\n4. Bank Secrecy Act enforcement cases\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Created frameworks for detecting potential money laundering activities\n\n5. Basel Committee recommendations\n- International standards for anti-money laundering protocols\n- Influenced global legal approaches\n\n6. Various Department of Justice prosecutions\n- Set precedents for prosecuting complex financial crimes\n- Established sentencing guidelines\n\nThese cases demonstrate evolving legal interpretations of money laundering statutes. However, specific details can vary based on jurisdiction and precise circumstances.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these precedents?",
